Blueprint: File System Fixture Format

Purpose
- Define a single, strict text format for representing a tree of files that our tooling can materialize into a real workspace.

Core Syntax
- Each file begins with a header line:
  // file: ./relative/path/from/repo/root.ext
- In case of nested fixtures within fixtures, the escaping of the file header line would have an additional leading //
  // file: ./relative/path/from/repo/root.ext
  //// file: ./i/am/a/file/in/the/inner/fixture.ext
- Immediately after the header, the file’s exact contents follow until the next header or end of document.
- Paths are POSIX-style and MUST begin with ./
- Empty files are represented by a header followed by nothing (or a single newline).
- By default, a fixture describes the full content of the files that should be created/updated. Files not listed are left untouched.
- The last occurrence of a given path in the same fixture wins. Avoid duplicates.
- Header lines MUST be unique and can appear in any order. Recommended: group by folder depth, then alphabetically for readability.
- Always add a version header in the first line, and bump it on each iteration -- version: vX
- Each fixture canvas must be code/other and should have it's own dedicated context. do not mix canvases context and override canvas of context A with context B, if needed create a new one


Comments & Prose
- The canvas itself is the source-of-truth; include only the headers and file contents.
- Do NOT wrap with Markdown fences.
- Do NOT add explanatory comments inside code files unless they are part of the file’s actual content.

Common Mistakes (don’t)
- Don’t include Markdown fences (``` … ```).
- Don’t omit ./ in paths.
- Don’t use Windows backslashes in paths.
- Don’t place prose between file blocks.
- Don’t add canvas comments; discuss in chat.

Versioning Note

Ready-to-Use Skeleton
// file: ./<path>/<name>.<ext>
<content>
// file: ./<another>/<path>/<name>.<ext>
<content>
//// file: ./<nested>/<file>/<name>.<ext>
<content>
